The collection includes canvases, sculptures, photos and even giant screens> showing entirely digital works. Among the strong pieces of the sale is "Emerging Faces" (estimated up to $250,000)> by American Pindar Van Arman: a series of nine paintings resulting from a "conversation" between two models of artificial intelligence. The first paints a face on a canvas and the second stops when it recognizes a human form.
<div </div
&nbsp;
The auction, as it was predictable, does not like all >ed an online petition was launched to ask for annulment, but without success. Many of the works presented "have been created using artificial intelligence models known for making unauthorized use of works protected by intellectual property law >", say petitioners who collected more than 6,300 signatures.
They believe that the event values the practice, comparing it to a "massive theft of the work of human artists" >. In 2023, several artists sued artificial intelligence startups, including the popular Midjourney and Stability AI platforms, accusing them of violating intellectual property laws.
But what do artists think? Refik Anadol, the great name of digital art > who participates in the auction with its animated creation "Machine Hallucinations", defended it that "most of the artists involved use their data and models", without drawing on other works. Signature of the petition, the Reid Southern illustrator, would like to exclude at least the works that do not use software or own data, a percentage of a third of the lots for sale.
<div </div
&nbsp;
"If it were ordinary paintings," he said, "and there was a high probability that many of them were counterfeit, the result of a theft or some questionable practice, it would not be ethical to proceed with the sale." "I am not an expert lawyer in intellectual property, so I cannot express myself on the legality of the process," says Nicole Sales Giles, "but the idea that artists take inspiration from their predecessors is not new >. Every new artistic movement arouses controversy and criticism," he adds. "Midjourney has been developed using almost everything on the Internet," says Turkish artist Sarp Kerem Yavuz, who used the software to compose "Hayal>", also auctioned by Christie's. "There are so many information used by the model that you cannot violate intellectual property rights of any particular element." "To rob one or two people would be wrong, but stealing millions of people would be acceptable?", Southern.&nbsp replica;
